968 si iam must be noted: when thus used, usually as here with a pres. subj., but not always, it means granting for the moment such or such for the sake of argument, yet that which is affirmes] will still follow, or that which is denied will still not follow: the reasoning therefore is, granting for the moment space to be finite, yet none the less the general conclusion will be true that the omne is infinite ; it therefore introduces another proof of this fact ; and has nothing to do with proving space to be infinite : the demonstration of that begins at 988 (984): comp. 111 540 si iam libeat concedere falsum Et dare...Mortalem tamen cet. 3 v 195 Quod si iam rerum iquorem primordia quae sint, Hoc tamen cet.: also 1 396 with imperf.
